<h2>Why Dryer Vent Maintenance Is a Fire Safety Issue in Pacific Palisades Right Now</h2>
<p>Across our LG Dryer Repair calls in Pacific Palisades the pattern clusters by neighborhood: Huntington Palisades' older flat homes drive thermal-fuse jobs from decades-old vents plus rebuild dust, The Highlands and hillside Castellammare and Riviera bring coastal corrosion and unconventional-vent assessments, and rebuilt homes across the area bring new-installation verification.</p>
<p>A dryer vent fire is one of the most preventable residential fire causes — and in Pacific Palisades in 2025, that prevention matters more than it did before January. Here is what we're seeing and why maintenance is urgent:</p>

<p><strong>Ash and particulate in surviving homes.</strong> Homes that came through the fire intact but were evacuated for weeks or months have exterior vent caps that accumulated fine ash and particulate. This material enters through the exterior cap during vacancy. The machine runs fine when the family returns — then d80 codes appear weeks later as the accumulated material restricts airflow further. Restricted airflow means the dryer runs hotter than it should on every cycle. That heat, combined with lint and ash particulate near the heating element, is exactly the condition that causes dryer fires. A vent cleaning and cap inspection ($150–200) eliminates this risk before it becomes a problem. We've done over a dozen returning-resident calls in Pacific Palisades since February 2025. The pattern is consistent: the machine runs normally for 2–3 weeks, then d80 codes start appearing. Every returning Palisades resident with an LG dryer should have this done before the machine completes its first 20 cycles.</p>

<p><strong>Construction dust in the active rebuild zone.</strong> Even homes that are occupied and functioning normally are in a neighborhood with active demolition and construction on surrounding streets. The January 2025 fires — both the Palisades Fire and the Eaton Fire in Altadena — created a regional awareness of fire prevention we're seeing across the Westside. Fine construction dust — drywall compound, wood particulate, concrete dust — enters exterior vent caps during the day and settles in duct systems faster than in normal conditions. We recommend vent inspection every 6 months for any Pacific Palisades home within a few blocks of active reconstruction.</p>

<p><strong>New dryer installations in rebuilt homes — vent verification is fire safety.</strong> A general contractor who installs a dryer vent as part of a rebuild is not an LG dryer technician. Construction vents are frequently installed with runs that are too long, bends that exceed code limits, or exterior caps in locations that partially restrict airflow. A new DLGX3901 or DLEX3900 running in a vent installation that doesn't meet LG specifications will overheat on every cycle — and in a brand-new rebuilt home in a fire-risk neighborhood, that is a preventable hazard. We verify new installations for $65 — waived if we find and fix a correction. Thirty minutes. The most important dryer call we do in the Palisades right now.</p>

<p><strong>Marine layer and electrical components.</strong> Pacific Palisades sits at the ocean's edge — marine layer is dense here for much of the year. Condensation from repeated marine layer exposure gets into electrical connections on DLEX and DLGX models over time. We apply marine-grade dielectric grease to sensitive connections on every Palisades call as a preventive measure — protects connectors and control board connections from moisture intrusion that causes intermittent failures.</p>

